[src:oberon-language/active-oberon] As it is tradition in the Oberon world, the Active Oberon language compiler is implemented in Active Oberon.
[src:oberon-language/active-oberon] The operating system, especially the kernel, synchronizes and coordinates different active objects.
[src:oberon-language/active-oberon] Active Oberon was renamed *Active Object System* (AOS) in 2002, then due to trademark issues, renamed *Bluebottle* in 2005, and then renamed *A2* in 2008.
[src:oberon-language/active-oberon] An Active Oberon fork is the language Zonnon.
[src:oberon-language/component-pascal] An open-source software implementation of Component Pascal exists for the .NET and Java virtual machine (JVM) platforms, from the Gardens Point team around John Gough at Queensland University of Technology in Australia.
[src:oberon-language/component-pascal] On 23 June 2004 Oberon microsystems announced that the BlackBox Component Builder was made available as a free download and that an open-source version was planned.
[src:oberon-language/component-pascal] The beta open-source version was initially released in December 2004 and updated to a final v1.5 release in December 2005.
[src:oberon-language/component-pascal] It includes the complete source code of the IDE, compiler, debugger, source analyser, profiler, and interfacing libraries, and can also be downloaded from their website.
[src:oberon-language/component-pascal] Several release candidates for v1.6 appeared in the years 2009–2011, the latest one (1.6rc6) appeared on Oberon microsystems web pages in 2011.
[src:oberon-language/component-pascal] At the end of 2013, Oberon microsystems released the final release 1.6.
[src:oberon-language/component-pascal] It is probably the last release bundled by them.
[src:oberon-language/component-pascal] A small community took over the ongoing development.
[src:oberon-language/component-pascal] BlackBox Component Pascal uses the extensions .odc (***O**beron **d**o**c**ument)*for document files, such as source files, and .osf *(**O**beron **s**ymbol **f**ile*) for symbol files while Gardens Point Component Pascal uses .cp for source and .cps for symbol files.
[src:oberon-language/component-pascal] BlackBox Component Pascal has its own executable and loadable object format .ocf (***O**beron **c**ode **f**ile*); it includes a runtime linking loader for this format.
[src:oberon-language/component-pascal] The document format (.odc) is a rich text binary format, which allows formatting, supports conditional folding, and allows active content to be embedded in the source text.
[src:oberon-language/component-pascal] It also handles user interface elements in editable forms.
[src:oberon-language/component-pascal] This is in the tradition of the Oberon Text format.
[src:oberon-language/component-pascal] The full syntax for CP, as given by the Language Report, is shown below.
[src:oberon-language/component-pascal] In the extended Backus–Naur form, only 34 grammatical productions are needed, one more than for Oberon-2, although it is a more advanced language.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] In computer science, **garbage collection** (**GC**) is a form of automatic memory management.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] The *garbage collector* attempts to reclaim memory that was allocated by the program, but is no longer referenced; such memory is called *garbage*.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] Garbage collection was invented by American computer scientist John McCarthy around 1959 to simplify manual memory management in Lisp.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] Garbage collection relieves the programmer from doing manual memory management, where the programmer specifies what objects to de-allocate and return to the memory system and when to do so.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] Other, similar techniques include stack allocation, region inference, and memory ownership, and combinations thereof.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] Garbage collection may take a significant proportion of a program's total processing time, and affect performance as a result.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] Resources other than memory, such as network sockets, database handles, windows, file descriptors, and device descriptors, are not typically handled by garbage collection, but rather by other methods (e.g. destructors).
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] Some such methods de-allocate memory also.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] Many programming languages require garbage collection, either as part of the language specification (e.g., RPL, Java, C#, D, Go, and most scripting languages) or effectively for practical implementation (e.g., formal languages like lambda calculus).
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] These are said to be *garbage-collected languages*.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] Other languages, such as C and C++, were designed for use with manual memory management, but have garbage-collected implementations available.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] Some languages, like Ada, Modula-3, and C++/CLI, allow both garbage collection and manual memory management to co-exist in the same application by using separate heaps for collected and manually managed objects.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] Still others, like D, are garbage-collected but allow the user to manually delete objects or even disable garbage collection entirely when speed is required.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] Although many languages integrate GC into their compiler and runtime system, *post-hoc* GC systems also exist, such as Automatic Reference Counting (ARC).
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] Some of these *post-hoc* GC systems do not require recompilation.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] GC frees the programmer from manually de-allocating memory.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] GC uses computing resources to decide which memory to free.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] Therefore, the penalty for the convenience of not annotating object lifetime manually in the source code is overhead, which can impair program performance.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] A peer-reviewed paper from 2005 concluded that GC needs five times the memory to compensate for this overhead and to perform as fast as the same program using idealized explicit memory management.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] The comparison however is made to a program generated by inserting deallocation calls using an oracle, implemented by collecting traces from programs run under a profiler, and the program is only correct for one particular execution of the program.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] Interaction with memory hierarchy effects can make this overhead intolerable in circumstances that are hard to predict or to detect in routine testing.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] The impact on performance was given by Apple as a reason for not adopting garbage collection in iOS, despite it being the most desired feature.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] The moment when the garbage is actually collected can be unpredictable, resulting in stalls (pauses to shift/free memory) scattered throughout a session.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] Unpredictable stalls can be unacceptable in real-time environments, in transaction processing, or in interactive programs.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] Incremental, concurrent, and real-time garbage collectors address these problems, with varying trade-offs.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] Tracing garbage collection is the most common type of garbage collection, so much so that "garbage collection" often refers to tracing garbage collection, rather than other methods such as reference counting.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] The overall strategy consists of determining which objects should be garbage collected by tracing which objects are *reachable* by a chain of references from certain root objects, and considering the rest as garbage and collecting them.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] However, there are a large number of algorithms used in implementation, with widely varying complexity and performance characteristics.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] Reference counting garbage collection is where each object has a count of the number of references to it.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] Garbage is identified by having a reference count of zero.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] An object's reference count is incremented when a reference to it is created and decremented when a reference is destroyed.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] When the count reaches zero, the object's memory is reclaimed.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] If two or more objects refer to each other, they can create a cycle whereby neither will be collected as their mutual references never let their reference counts become zero.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] ) use specific cycle-detecting algorithms to deal with this issue.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] for the "backpointers" which create cycles.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] Under reference counting, a weak reference is similar to a weak reference under a tracing garbage collector.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] It is a special reference object whose existence does not increment the reference count of the referent object.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] , rather than being permitted to remain dangling, meaning that it turns into a predictable value, such as a null reference.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] Reference counting requires space to be allocated for each object to store its reference count.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] The count may be stored adjacent to the object's memory or in a side table somewhere else, but in either case, every single reference-counted object requires additional storage for its reference count.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] Memory space with the size of an unsigned pointer is commonly used for this task, meaning that 32 or 64 bits of reference count storage must be allocated for each object.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] to store the reference count in unused areas of the object's memory.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] Often, an architecture does not actually allow programs to access the full range of memory addresses that could be stored in its native pointer size; a certain number of high bits in the address is either ignored or required to be zero.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] If an object reliably has a pointer at a certain location, the reference count can be stored in the unused bits of the pointer.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] , 19 unused bits of this class pointer are used to store the object's reference count.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] In naive implementations, each assignment of a reference and each reference falling out of scope often require modifications of one or more reference counters.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] However, in a common case when a reference is copied from an outer scope variable into an inner scope variable, such that the lifetime of the inner variable is bounded by the lifetime of the outer one, the reference incrementing can be eliminated.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] The outer variable "owns" the reference.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] whose constructors, destructors, and assignment operators manage the references.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] A smart pointer can be passed by reference to a function, which avoids the need to copy-construct a new smart pointer (which would increase the reference count on entry into the function and decrease it on exit).
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] Instead, the function receives a reference to the smart pointer which is produced inexpensively.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] The Deutsch-Bobrow method of reference counting capitalizes on the fact that most reference count updates are in fact generated by references stored in local variables.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] It ignores these references, only counting references in the heap, but before an object with reference count zero can be deleted, the system must verify with a scan of the stack and register that no other reference to it still exists.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] Consider a pointer that in a given interval of the execution is updated several times.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] But most of these updates are redundant.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] Levanoni and Petrank measured an elimination of more than 99% of the counter updates in typical Java benchmarks.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] , at least for any objects which are shared, or potentially shared among multiple threads.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] Atomic operations are expensive on a multiprocessor, and even more expensive if they have to be emulated with software algorithms.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] can be used to eliminate all atomic operations from the write-barrier.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] Counters are never updated by the program threads in the course of program execution.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] They are only modified by the collector which executes as a single additional thread with no synchronization.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] This method can be used as a stop-the-world mechanism for parallel programs, and also with a concurrent reference counting collector.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] Naive implementations of reference counting do not generally provide real-time behavior, because any pointer assignment can potentially cause a number of objects bounded only by total allocated memory size to be recursively freed while the thread is unable to perform other work.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] It is possible to avoid this issue by delegating the freeing of unreferenced objects to other threads, at the cost of extra overhead.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] Escape analysis is a compile-time technique that can convert heap allocations to stack allocations, thereby reducing the amount of garbage collection to be done.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] This analysis determines whether an object allocated inside a function is accessible outside of it.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] If a function-local allocation is found to be accessible to another function or thread, the allocation is said to "escape" and cannot be done on the stack.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] Otherwise, the object may be allocated directly on the stack and released when the function returns, bypassing the heap and associated memory management costs.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] Generally speaking, higher-level programming languages are more likely to have garbage collection as a standard feature.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] In some languages lacking built-in garbage collection, it can be added through a library, as with the Boehm garbage collector for C and C++.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] Most functional programming languages, such as ML, Haskell, and APL, have garbage collection built in.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] Lisp is especially notable as both the first functional programming language and the first language to introduce garbage collection.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] Other dynamic languages, such as Ruby and Julia (but not Perl 5 or PHP before version 5.3, which both use reference counting), JavaScript and ECMAScript also tend to use GC.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] Object-oriented programming languages such as Smalltalk, ooRexx, RPL and Java usually provide integrated garbage collection.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] Notable exceptions are C++ and Delphi, which have destructors.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] BASIC and Logo have often used garbage collection for variable-length data types, such as strings and lists, so as not to burden programmers with memory management details.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] On the Altair 8800, programs with many string variables and little string space could cause long pauses due to garbage collection.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] Similarly the Applesoft BASIC interpreter's garbage collection algorithm repeatedly scans the string descriptors for the string having the highest address in order to compact it toward high memory, resulting in $O(n^{2})$ performance and pauses anywhere from a few seconds to a few minutes.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] A replacement garbage collector for Applesoft BASIC by Randy Wigginton identifies a group of strings in every pass over the heap, reducing collection time dramatically.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] BASIC.SYSTEM, released with ProDOS in 1983, provides a windowing garbage collector for BASIC that is many times faster.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] C has never offered official support for garbage collection.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] C++ added garbage collection support in C++11 to the standard library, however this was removed in C++23 due to no compilers implementing support for the feature.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] The features that were part of this were related to pointer safety.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] Although garbage collection support in the standard library was removed, some garbage collectors such as Boehm garbage collector (for C and C++) can still be used.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] Boehm GC uses mark-and-sweep garbage collection.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] It can also be used in leak detection mode, where memory management is still manual however leaks and double-free errors can be detected and reported.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] Its use can be called from the header `<gc.h>`.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] One can still abstract away manual object destructions in C++ by using the "resource acquisition is initialization" (RAII) idiom and smart pointers.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] `std::unique_ptr` ties lifetimes to ownership, while `std::shared_ptr` uses reference counting to determine lifetime.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] `std::weak_ptr` can be used to obtain a pointer without increasing the reference count.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] Unlike garbage collection, RAII is deterministic.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] While the Objective-C traditionally had no garbage collection, with the release of OS X 10.5 in 2007 Apple introduced garbage collection for Objective-C 2.0, using an in-house developed runtime collector.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] However, with the 2012 release of OS X 10.8, garbage collection was deprecated in favor of LLVM's automatic reference counter (ARC) that was introduced with OS X 10.7.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] Furthermore, since May 2015 Apple even forbade the usage of garbage collection for new OS X applications in the App Store.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] For iOS, garbage collection has never been introduced due to problems in application responsivity and performance; instead, iOS uses ARC.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] Garbage collection is rarely used on embedded or real-time systems because of the usual need for very tight control over the use of limited resources.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] However, garbage collectors compatible with many limited environments have been developed.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] The Microsoft .NET Micro Framework, .NET nanoFramework and Java Platform, Micro Edition are embedded software platforms that, like their larger cousins, include garbage collection.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] Compile-time garbage collection is a form of static analysis allowing memory to be reused and reclaimed based on invariants known during compilation.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] This form of garbage collection has been studied in the Mercury programming language, and it saw greater usage with the introduction of LLVM's automatic reference counter (ARC) into Apple's ecosystem (iOS and OS X) in 2011.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] Incremental, concurrent, and real-time garbage collectors have been developed, for example by Henry Baker and by Henry Lieberman.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] In Baker's algorithm, the allocation is done in either half of a single region of memory.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] When it becomes half full, a garbage collection is performed which moves the live objects into the other half and the remaining objects are implicitly deallocated.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] The running program (the 'mutator') has to check that any object it references is in the correct half, and if not move it across, while a background task is finding all of the objects.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] Generational garbage collection schemes are based on the empirical observation that most objects die young.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] In generational garbage collection, two or more allocation regions (generations) are kept, which are kept separate based on the object's age.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] New objects are created in the "young" generation that is regularly collected, and when a generation is full, the objects that are still referenced from older regions are copied into the next oldest generation.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] Some high-level language computer architectures include hardware support for real-time garbage collection.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] Most implementations of real-time garbage collectors use tracing.
[src:oberon-language/garbage-collection-computer-science] Such real-time garbage collectors meet hard real-time constraints when used with a real-time operating system.
[src:oberon-language/modular-programming] A module interface expresses the elements that are provided and required by the module.
[src:oberon-language/modular-programming] The elements defined in the interface are detectable by other modules.
[src:oberon-language/modular-programming] The implementation contains the working code that corresponds to the elements declared in the interface.
[src:oberon-language/modular-programming] Modular programming, in the form of subsystems (particularly for I/O) and software libraries, dates to early software systems, where it was used for code reuse.
[src:oberon-language/modular-programming] Modular programming per se, with a goal of modularity, developed in the late 1960s and 1970s, as a larger-scale analog of the concept of structured programming (1960s).
[src:oberon-language/modular-programming] The term "modular programming" dates at least to the National Symposium on Modular Programming, organized at the Information and Systems Institute in July 1968 by Larry Constantine; other key concepts were information hiding (1972) and separation of concerns (SoC, 1974).
[src:oberon-language/modular-programming] Modules were not included in the original specification for ALGOL 68 (1968), but were included as extensions in early implementations, ALGOL 68-R (1970) and ALGOL 68C (1970), and later formalized.
[src:oberon-language/modular-programming] One of the first languages designed from the start for modular programming was the short-lived Modula (1975), by Niklaus Wirth.
[src:oberon-language/modular-programming] Another early modular language was Mesa (1970s), by Xerox PARC, and Wirth drew on Mesa as well as the original Modula in its successor, Modula-2 (1978), which influenced later languages, particularly through its successor, Modula-3 (1980s).
[src:oberon-language/modular-programming] Modula's use of dot-qualified names, like `M.a` to refer to object `a` from module `M`, coincides with notation to access a field of a record (and similarly for attributes or methods of objects), and is now widespread, seen in C++, C#, Dart, Go, Java, OCaml, and Python, among others.
[src:oberon-language/modular-programming] Modular programming became widespread from the 1980s: the original Pascal language (1970) did not include modules, but later versions, notably UCSD Pascal (1978) and Turbo Pascal (1983) included them in the form of "units", as did the Pascal-influenced Ada (1980).
[src:oberon-language/modular-programming] The Extended Pascal ISO 10206:1990 standard kept closer to Modula2 in its modular support.
[src:oberon-language/modular-programming] Standard ML (1984) has one of the most complete module systems, including functors (parameterized modules) to map between modules.
[src:oberon-language/modular-programming] In the 1980s and 1990s, modular programming was overshadowed by and often conflated with object-oriented programming, particularly due to the popularity of C++ and Java.
[src:oberon-language/modular-programming] For example, the C family of languages had support for objects and classes in C++ (originally C with Classes, 1980) and Objective-C (1983), only supporting modules 30 years or more later.
[src:oberon-language/modular-programming] Java (1995) supports modules in the form of packages, though the primary unit of code organization is a class.
[src:oberon-language/modular-programming] However, Python (1991) prominently used both modules and objects from the start, using modules as the primary unit of code organization and "packages" as a larger-scale unit.
[src:oberon-language/modular-programming] Perl 5 (1994) also includes support for both modules and objects, with a vast array of modules being available from CPAN (1993).
[src:oberon-language/modular-programming] OCaml (1996) followed ML by supporting modules and functors.
[src:oberon-language/modular-programming] Modular programming is now widespread, and found in virtually all major languages developed since the 1990s.
[src:oberon-language/modular-programming] The relative importance of modules varies between languages, and in class-based object-oriented languages there is still overlap and confusion with classes as a unit of organization and encapsulation, but these are both well-established as distinct concepts.
[src:oberon-language/modular-programming] The term *assembly* (as in .NET languages like C#, F#, or Visual Basic) or *package* (as in Dart, Go, or Java) is sometimes used instead of *module*.
[src:oberon-language/modular-programming] In other implementations, these are distinct concepts; in Python a package is a set of modules, while in Java 9 the introduction of the Java Platform Module System, in which a new module concept, involving a set of packages with enhanced access control, was implemented.
[src:oberon-language/modular-programming] In Java, the term *package* is used for the module concept in the Java language specification.
[src:oberon-language/modular-programming] The *module*, a kind of set of a package, was introduced in Java 9.
[src:oberon-language/modular-programming] In some Pascal dialects, the term *unit* is used for the module concept.
[src:oberon-language/modular-programming] A component is a similar concept, but typically refers to a higher level; a component is a piece of a whole system, while a module is a piece of an individual program.
[src:oberon-language/modular-programming] The scale of the term "module" varies significantly between languages; in Python it is very small-scale and each file is a module, while in Java 9 it is large-scale, where a module is a set of packages, which are in turn sets of files.
[src:oberon-language/modular-programming] Conspicuous examples of languages that lack support for modules are C, and in their original forms, C++ and Pascal.
[src:oberon-language/modular-programming] C and C++ do, however, allow separate compilation and declarative interfaces to be specified using header files which is commonly considered modularization.
[src:oberon-language/modular-programming] Modules were added to Objective-C in iOS 7 (2013), and to C++ with C++20.
[src:oberon-language/modular-programming] Pascal was superseded by Modula and Oberon, which included modules from the start, and various derivatives that included modules.
[src:oberon-language/modular-programming] JavaScript has had native modules since ECMAScript 2015.
[src:oberon-language/modular-programming] C++ modules have allowed backwards compatibility with headers (with "header units").
[src:oberon-language/modular-programming] Dialects of C allow for modules, for example Clang supports modules for the C language, though the syntax and semantics of Clang C modules differ from C++ modules.
[src:oberon-language/modular-programming] Modular programming can be performed even where the programming language lacks explicit syntactic features to support named modules, like, for example, in C.
[src:oberon-language/modular-programming] This is done by using existing language features, together with, for example, coding conventions, programming idioms and the physical code structure.
[src:oberon-language/modular-programming] IBM i also uses modules when programming in the Integrated Language Environment (ILE).
[src:oberon-language/modular-programming] With modular programming, concerns are separated such that modules perform logically discrete functions, interacting through well-defined interfaces.
[src:oberon-language/modular-programming] Often modules form a directed acyclic graph (DAG); in this case a cyclic dependency between modules is seen as indicating that these should be a single module.
[src:oberon-language/modular-programming] In the case where modules do form a DAG they can be arranged as a hierarchy, where the lowest-level modules are independent, depending on no other modules, and higher-level modules depend on lower-level ones.
[src:oberon-language/modular-programming] A particular program or library is a top-level module of its own hierarchy, but can in turn be seen as a lower-level module of a higher-level program, library, or system.
[src:oberon-language/modular-programming] When creating a modular system, instead of creating a monolithic application (where the smallest component is the whole), several smaller modules are written separately so when they are composed together, they construct the executable application program.
[src:oberon-language/modular-programming] Typically, these are also compiled separately, via separate compilation, and then linked by a linker.
[src:oberon-language/modular-programming] A just-in-time compiler may perform some of this construction "on-the-fly" at run time.
[src:oberon-language/modular-programming] These independent functions are commonly classified as either program control functions or specific task functions.
[src:oberon-language/modular-programming] Program control functions are designed to work for one program.
[src:oberon-language/modular-programming] Specific task functions are closely prepared to be applicable for various programs.
[src:oberon-language/modular-programming] This makes modular designed systems, if built correctly, far more reusable than a traditional monolithic design, since all (or many) of these modules may then be reused (without change) in other projects.
[src:oberon-language/modular-programming] This also facilitates the "breaking down" of projects into several smaller projects.
[src:oberon-language/modular-programming] Theoretically, a modularized software project will be more easily assembled by large teams, since no team members are creating the whole system, or even need to know about the system as a whole.
[src:oberon-language/modular-programming] They can focus just on the assigned smaller task.
[src:oberon-language/niklaus-wirth] Niklaus Emil Wirth was born in Winterthur, Switzerland, on 15 February 1934.
[src:oberon-language/niklaus-wirth] He was the son of Hedwig (née Keller) and Walter Wirth, a high school teacher.
[src:oberon-language/niklaus-wirth] Wirth studied electronic engineering at the Federal Institute of Technology, Zürich (ETH Zürich) from 1954 to 1958, graduating with a Bachelor of Science (B.S.) degree.
[src:oberon-language/niklaus-wirth] In 1960, he earned a Master of Science (M.Sc.) from Université Laval in Quebec.
[src:oberon-language/niklaus-wirth] Then in 1963, he was awarded a PhD in electrical engineering and computer science (EECS) from the University of California, Berkeley, supervised by computer design pioneer Harry Huskey.
[src:oberon-language/niklaus-wirth] From 1963 to 1967, Wirth served as assistant professor of computer science at Stanford University and again at the University of Zürich.
[src:oberon-language/niklaus-wirth] In 1968, he became a professor of informatics at ETH Zürich, taking two one-year sabbaticals at Xerox PARC in California (1976–1977 and 1984–1985).
[src:oberon-language/niklaus-wirth] He was also a major part of the design and implementation team for the operating systems Medos-2 (1983, for the Lilith workstation) and Oberon (1987, for the Ceres workstation), and for the Lola (1995) digital hardware design and simulation system.
[src:oberon-language/niklaus-wirth] In 1984, Wirth received the Association for Computing Machinery (ACM) Turing Award for the development of these languages.
[src:oberon-language/niklaus-wirth] In 1994, he was inducted as a Fellow of the ACM.
[src:oberon-language/niklaus-wirth] In 1999, he received the ACM SIGSOFT Outstanding Research Award.
[src:oberon-language/niklaus-wirth] In 1995, he popularized the adage now named Wirth's law.
[src:oberon-language/niklaus-wirth] The April 1971 *Communications of the ACM* article "Program Development by Stepwise Refinement", concerning the teaching of programming, is considered to be a classic text in software engineering.
[src:oberon-language/niklaus-wirth] The paper is considered to be the earliest work to formally outline the top-down method for designing programs.
[src:oberon-language/niklaus-wirth] The article was discussed by Fred Brooks in his influential book *The Mythical Man-Month* and was described as "seminal" in the ACM's brief biography of Wirth published in connection to his Turing Award.
[src:oberon-language/niklaus-wirth] The 1973 textbook *Systematic Programming: An Introduction* was described as a quality source for mathematicians desiring to understand the nature of programming in a 1974 review.
[src:oberon-language/niklaus-wirth] In 1974, *The Pascal User Manual and Report*, jointly written with Kathleen Jensen, served as the basis of many language implementation efforts in the 1970s (BSD Pascal), and 1980s in the United States and across Europe.
[src:oberon-language/niklaus-wirth] In 1975, he wrote the book *Algorithms + Data Structures = Programs*, which gained wide recognition.
[src:oberon-language/niklaus-wirth] Major revisions of this book with the new title *Algorithms & Data Structures* were published in 1986 and 2004.
[src:oberon-language/niklaus-wirth] The examples in the first edition were written in Pascal.
[src:oberon-language/niklaus-wirth] These were replaced in the later editions with examples written in Modula-2 and Oberon, respectively.
[src:oberon-language/niklaus-wirth] In 1992, Wirth and Jürg Gutknecht published the full documentation of the Oberon operating system.
[src:oberon-language/niklaus-wirth] A second book, with Martin Reiser, was intended as a programming guide.
[src:oberon-language/niklaus-wirth] Wirth died in Zürich on New Year's Day 2024, at age 89.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] The **Oberon System** is a modular, single-user, single-process, multitasking operating system written in the programming language Oberon.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] It was originally developed in the late 1980s at ETH Zurich.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] The Oberon System has an unconventional visual text user interface (TUI) instead of a conventional command-line interface (CLI) or graphical user interface (GUI).
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] This TUI was very innovative in its time.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] It influenced the design of the Acme text editor for the Plan 9 from Bell Labs operating system and bears some similarities to the "Look and feel" of the worksheet interface of the Macintosh Programmer's Workshop.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] The system also evolved into the multi-process, symmetric multiprocessing (SMP) capable A2 (formerly *Active Object System* (AOS), then *Bluebottle*), with a zooming user interface (ZUI).
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] The Oberon operating system originated as part of the NS32032-based Ceres workstation project.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] It was written almost entirely (and in the 2013 version entirely is valid) in the Oberon programming language.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] The basic system was designed and implemented by Niklaus Wirth and Jürg Gutknecht and its design and implementation is fully documented in their book "Project Oberon".
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] The user Interface and programmers reference is found in Martin Reiser's book "The Oberon System".
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] The Oberon System was later extended and ported to other hardware platforms by a team at ETH Zurich and there was recognition in popular magazines.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] Wirth and Gutknecht (although being active computer science professors) refer to themselves as 'part-time programmers' in the book *Project Oberon*.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] In late 2013, a few months before his 80th birthday, Wirth published a second edition of Project Oberon.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] It details implementing the Oberon System using a reduced instruction set computer (RISC) CPU of his own design realized on a Xilinx field-programmable gate array (FPGA) board.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] It was presented at the symposium organized for his 80th birthday at ETH Zurich.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] In the meantime, several emulators for this version were implemented.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] Oberon has a text user interface (TUI), which is very different from a terminal user interface.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] It combines the point and click convenience of a graphical user interface (GUI) with the linguistic strength of a command-line interface (CLI) and is closely tied to the naming conventions of the Oberon language.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] Text appearing almost anywhere on a screen can be edited and used as command input.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] Commands are activated by a middle-mouse click on a text fragment of the form `Module.Command` (optionally followed by parameters, which are terminated by `~`).
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] A command is defined by any procedure which is exported and has an empty argument list.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] Parameters to the command must be defined before executing the middle click, and must be explicitly scanned and retrieved by the procedure.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] No checks or questions occur during command execution.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] This is sometimes called a *non-modal* user interface (UI).
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] V1 was the first usable version some time before the Oberon Trilogy was published.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] A major change in the text model together with the editor named Write yielded V2.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] As foreshadowed in the table in section History above, there was a major fork in the early 1990s: V4 vs.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] System 3: The group around Jürg Gutknecht introduced persistent objects and object-libraries thereby extending the kernel.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] The group around Hanspeter Mössenböck realized similar features by introducing active elements mapped to a special character thereby extending fonts without changing the kernel.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] System 3 was sometimes also named Spirit of Oberon and later renamed ETH Oberon, whereas V4 was sometimes also named Linz Oberon.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] Differences between V2.2 and V4 are summarized by a PostScript document found at SourceForge which was converted to PDF and uploaded to Wikipedia.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] As of 2017, the Oberon OS is available for several hardware computing platforms, generally in no cost versions and from several sources, which is quite confusing.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] The Oberon OS is typically extremely compact.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] Even with an Oberon compiler, assorted utilities including a web browser, TCP/IP networking, and a GUI, the full package can be compressed to one 3.5" floppy disk.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] There are versions which emulated the Oberon OS on another operating system and versions which run on bare hardware.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] The latter ones are named Native Oberon.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] There are native versions for the Ceres, Intel IA-32, and ARM platforms.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] In 2013, Niklaus Wirth adapted the basic system as described in "Project Oberon" to a current FPGA design.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] According to the preface of the 2013 edition, the whole system compiles in less than 10 seconds on a Spartan-3 board.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] This version is sometimes also named V5, despite it being much more similar functionally to the original V1 running on the Ceres than any of the later versions.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] A version of the Oberon System 3, which is more integrated in the Microsoft Windows OS than other implementations was named Plugin Oberon.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] Plugin Oberon had support for OLE, Netscape Plugins, and the binary format named Oberon Module Interchange (OMI) or *slim binaries*, which allowed portable object code between Intel x86, Motorola 68K, and PowerPC architectures.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] Slim binaries were invented by Michael Franz in the early 1990s.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] They were motivated and opposed to the *fat binaries* invented by Apple during the transition from 68k to PowerPC architectures.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] OMI provided portable code based on a compressed version of the abstract syntax tree.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] The approach of a compressed abstract syntax tree for portable code representation is revived in the Java world for GraalVM and Truffle.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] The version named Oberon V4 (see also History) is closer to the original operating system developed by Wirth and Gutknecht.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] It was originally developed at ETHZ, but when H.P.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] Mössenböck went to Institut für Systemsoftware at Johannes-Kepler University in Linz (JKU), the development of V4 moved also.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] Thus, V4 is sometimes also called Linz-Oberon in contrast to ETH-Oberon.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] The most recent version of V4 and extensions are available at JKU link "Oberon from the Linz server", see also notes below.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] Oberon V4 appears to be orphaned, there are almost no changes since 2000.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] Another repository of V4 is Claudio Nieder's Oberon V4, which also shows difference between the different V4 implementations.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] Since 2013 this page moved to/is mirrored at SourceForge.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] V4 is closer to what would now be called an integrated development environment than an operating system of its own.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] There were many extensions written for V4, which are still available in the directory LinzTools of the zip archive of the former ftp-download area from the server of SSW at JKU.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] Some documentation can be found on their web-pages.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] The links on this page are all dead, but pointed to *.Cod files in Oberon/LinzTools directory on the ftp-server, which are mirrored in the subdirectory Oberon/Oberon/LinzTools of the previously mentioned zip-archive.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] More information is normally included in the packages and it is given in Oberon's special rich text format.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] The commands for extracting these from the ASCII formatted *.Cod files are generally present in the first lines of the *.Cod files.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] It is available from ETH Zurich with most source via the Internet.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] Native versions of A2 run on single- and multi-processor IA-32 and x86-64 hardware, both on bare metal and inside virtual machines.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] It was previously also available for the StrongARM CPU family.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] Versions which execute as programs under other operating systems are available on Windows (WinAos), Unix (UnixAos), Linux (LinuxAos), and macOS (DarwinAos).
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] More detailed information about A2 is on the Russian Wikipedia pages about A2.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] As a part of an industrial research project the Native Systems Group of ETH Zurich has developed an application-specific operating system named *stailaOS* which is based on the latest version Oberon OS.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] It is intended for uses such as real-time analytics, financial applications, main memory based enterprise resource planning (ERP), etc.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] Native Oberon is an Oberon System that runs on bare hardware.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] *PC-Native Oberon* is a version that runs on IA-32 PC hardware.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] There has never been a V4 Native Oberon, so all information in this section implicitly assumes that it is System 3.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] Native Oberon has small hardware requirements: 133 MHz Pentium, 100MB hard disk, VESA 2 graphics card with resolution minimum of 1024x768 pixels, optional 3Com network card.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] The basic system runs from one HD floppy disk, and more software can be installed through a network.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] The full installation includes the Gadgets GUI.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] It is written fully in the language Oberon.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] January 2003 and sometimes also labeled as Update/Alpha, especially on the ftp-server of ETHZ.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] Later versions were incorporated in AOS/BlueBottle/A2.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] A version named Linux Native Oberon (LNO) uses Linux as a hardware abstraction layer (HAL).
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] Its goal is to be as compatible as possible to PC-Native Oberon.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] Other versions of the Oberon System, without *Native* in the name, had partly modified interfaces of low level modules.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] In 2015, Peter Matthias revitalized LNO under the name Oberon Linux Revival (OLR) as a multi-platform distribution running seamlessly on Intel x86, ARM, MIPS, and RISC-V.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] It runs well on the Raspberry Pi and on the low cost (discontinued) CHIP computer; with some tweaking (adjusting group membership or/and permissions on some devices) it runs well on Tiny Core Linux.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] OLR interfaces with Linux kernel by direct system calls.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] As of June 2017, OLR lacks a network layer.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] In 2013, Wirth and Paul Reed completed a re-implementation of the original Oberon System for the Digilent Xilinx Spartan 3 FPGA Starter Board.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] The work includes a revision of "Project Oberon", identified as "Project Oberon (New Edition 2013)".
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] In 2015, Reed collaborated with Victor Yurkovsky to create OberonStation, a Xilinx Spartan 3-based computer designed specifically to run Oberon.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] The system has since been ported to a Xilinx Spartan 6 FPGA Pepino development board by Saanlima Electronics, and a Xilinx Artix 7-based Digilent Nexys A7-100 FPGA Trainer board by CFB Software.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-operating-system] Peter de Wachter implemented an emulator for it, which was also ported to Java and JavaScript by Michael Schierl, running in modern browsers.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-programming-language] Oberon was maintained by Wirth and the latest Project Oberon compiler update is dated 6 March 2020.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-programming-language] Oberon is designed with a motto attributed to Albert Einstein in mind: "Make things as simple as possible, but not simpler." The principal guideline was to concentrate on features that are basic and essential and to omit ephemeral issues.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-programming-language] Another factor was recognition of the growth of complexity in languages such as C++ and Ada.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-programming-language] In contrast to these, Oberon emphasizes the use of the library concept to extend the language.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-programming-language] Enumeration and subrange types, which were present in Modula-2, were omitted, and set types are limited to sets of integers.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-programming-language] All imported items must be qualified by the name of the module where they are declared.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-programming-language] Low-level facilities are highlighted by only allowing them to be used in a module which includes the identifier `SYSTEM` in its import list.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-programming-language] Strict type checking, even across modules, and index checking at runtime, null pointer checking, and the safe type extension concept largely allow programming to rely on the language rules alone.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-programming-language] The intent of this strategy was to produce a language that is easier to learn, simpler to implement, and very efficient.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-programming-language] Oberon compilers have been viewed as compact and fast, while providing code quality comparable to commercial compilers.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-programming-language] Oberon supports extension of record types for the construction of abstractions and heterogeneous structures.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-programming-language] In contrast to the later dialects, Oberon-2 and Active Oberon, the original Oberon lacks a dispatch mechanism as a language feature but has it as a programming technique or design pattern.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-programming-language] In the Oberon operating system, two programming techniques are used together for the dispatch call: Method suite and Message handler.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-programming-language] Dynamic dispatch is only done via procedures in Figures module that is the generic module.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-programming-language] In the Oberon operating system both of these techniques are used for dynamic dispatch.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-programming-language] The first one is used for a known set of methods; the second is used for any new methods declared in the extension module.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-programming-language] For example, if the extension module Rectangles were to implement a new Rotate() procedure, within the Figures module it could only be called via a message handler.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-programming-language] No-cost implementations of Oberon (the language) and Oberon (the operating system) can be found on the Internet (several are from ETHZ itself).
[src:oberon-language/oberon-programming-language] A few changes were made to the first released specification.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-programming-language] For example, object-oriented programming (OOP) features were added, the `FOR` loop was reinstated.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-programming-language] One release, named *Native Oberon* which includes an operating system, and can directly boot on IBM PC compatible class hardware.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-programming-language] A .NET implementation of Oberon with some added minor .NET-related extensions was also developed at ETHZ.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-programming-language] In 1993, an ETHZ university spin-off company brought a dialect of Oberon-2 to the market named *Oberon-L*.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-programming-language] In 1997, it was renamed *Component Pascal*.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-programming-language] Oberon-2 compilers developed by ETH include versions for Microsoft Windows, Linux, Solaris, and classic Mac OS.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-programming-language] Implementations from other sources exist for some other operating systems, including Atari TOS and AmigaOS.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-programming-language] There is an Oberon-2 Lex scanner and Yacc parser by Stephen J Bevan of Manchester University, UK, based on the one in the Mössenböck and Wirth reference.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-programming-language] Other compilers include Oxford Oberon-2, which also understands Oberon-07, and Vishap Oberon.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-programming-language] The latter is based on Josef Templ's Oberon to C language source-to-source compiler (transpiler) named Ofront, which in turn is based on the OP2 Compiler developed by Regis Crelier at ETHZ.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-programming-language] Oberon-07, defined by Niklaus Wirth in 2007 and revised in 2008, 2011, 2013, 2014, 2015, and 2016 is based on the original version of Oberon rather than Oberon-2.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-programming-language] Oberon-07 compilers have been developed for use with many different computer systems.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-programming-language] Wirth's compiler targets a reduced instruction set computer (RISC) processor of his own design that was used to implement the 2013 version of the Project Oberon operating system on a Xilinx field-programmable gate array (FPGA) Spartan-3 board.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-programming-language] Ports of the RISC processor to FPGA Spartan-6, Spartan-7, Artix-7 and a RISC emulator for Windows (compilable on Linux and macOS, and binaries available for Windows) also exist.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-programming-language] OBNC compiles via C and can be used on any Portable Operating System Interface (POSIX) compatible operating system.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-programming-language] The commercial Astrobe implementation targets STM ARM Cortex-M0, M3, M4, M7 and Raspberry Pi RP2040 and RP2350 microcontrollers.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-programming-language] The Patchouli compiler produces 64-bit Windows binaries.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-programming-language] Oberon-07M produces 32-bit Windows binaries and implements revision 2008 of the language.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-programming-language] Akron's produces binaries for both Windows and Linux.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-programming-language] OberonJS translates Oberon to JavaScript.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-programming-language] There is online IDE for Oberon. oberonc is an implementation for the Java virtual machine.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-programming-language] Active Oberon is yet another variant of Oberon, which adds objects (with object-centered access protection and local activity control), system-guarded assertions, preemptive priority scheduling and a changed syntax for methods (named *type-bound procedures* in Oberon vocabulary).
[src:oberon-language/oberon-programming-language] Objects may be active, which means that they may be threads or processes.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-programming-language] The operating system A2 (formerly *Active Object System* (AOS), then *Bluebottle*), especially the kernel, synchronizes and coordinates different active objects.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-programming-language] ETHZ has released Active Oberon which supports active objects, and the operating systems based thereon (Active Object System (AOS), Bluebottle, A2), and environment (JDK, HTTP, FTP, etc.) for the language.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-programming-language] As with many prior designs from ETHZ, versions of both are available for download on the Internet.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-programming-language] As of 2003, supported central processing units (CPUs) include single and dual core x86, and StrongARM.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-programming-language] Development continued on languages in this family.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-programming-language] A further extension of Oberon-2 was originally named Oberon/L but later renamed to Component Pascal (CP).
[src:oberon-language/oberon-programming-language] CP was developed for Windows and classic Mac OS by Oberon microsystems, a commercial spin-off company from ETHZ, and for .NET by Queensland University of Technology.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-programming-language] Further, the languages *Lagoona* and *Obliq* carry Oberon methods into specialized areas.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-programming-language] Later .NET development efforts at ETHZ focused on a new language named Zonnon.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-programming-language] This includes the features of Oberon and restores some from Pascal (enumerated types, built-in IO) but has some syntactic differences.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-programming-language] Other features include support for active objects, operator overloading, and exception handling.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-programming-language] Oberon-V (originally named Seneca, after Seneca the Younger) is a descendant of Oberon designed for numerical applications on supercomputers, especially vector or pipelined architectures.
[src:oberon-language/oberon-programming-language] It includes array constructors and an `ALL` statement.
